05568nam a22006615i 9780773549760DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735497607 a10.1515/97807735497602doi  a(DE-B1597)655154  a(OCoLC)971267414  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHT169.M628bO73 2017 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a307.1/2160956223  aMS 1850qBVB2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/123620:00aOrder and Disorder :bUrban Governance and the Making of Middle Eastern Cities /ced. by Luna Khirfan. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource :b14 photos, 5 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Urban Governance00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Urban Governance Conundrum in MENA -- tThe State and Civil Society -- tGoverning Majorities in the Arab World: Urban Life beyond Neoliberalism -- tCairo Unplanned: Informal Areas and the Politics of Urban Development -- tTracing Participatory Planning in Amman -- tThe State and the Market -- tExporting Dubai to Cairo or Capitalism by Proxy? -- tThe Processes of Neoliberal Governance and Urban Transformations in Amman, Jordan -- tThe Market and Civil Society -- tThe New Centre and the City Citizen -- tIslamized Postal Savings: A Model for Risk Sharing -- tConcluding Remarks: Order and Disorder in the Making of Middle Eastern Cities -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs Middle Eastern cities weather the second decade of the twenty-first century, they face a number of challenges to their economic resilience, competitiveness, and internal stability. In this uniquely tense realm for the urban public, an understanding of the dynamics of decision-making processes, citizen power, and the rule of law is critical to the direction of policy in the future. In Order and Disorder, Luna Khirfan weaves a cross-national comparison of Amman and Cairo that dissects the many layers and complexities of urban governance. Through case studies on a diverse array of development projects and their associated challenges, the contributors demonstrate how three actors – the state, the market, and civil society – interact with each other within the same urban political space. First, they argue that interplay between the state and civil society reveals the potential of urban majorities and the discords within current participatory planning. She then delves into the neoliberal dynamics between the state and the market, stressing the impact of economic push and pull factors on urban landscapes. The final chapters explain why the market’s relationship with civil society oscillates between exclusion and alienation. Throughout the book, Khirfan identifies the role of an authoritarian bargain in governing every one of these interactions. In light of current regional political instability in the Middle East and North Africa, Order and Disorder offers an arena for extrapolating lessons from urban governance to the wider political sphere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCities and townszMiddle EastvCase studies. 0aCity planningzMiddle EastvCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAbu-Hamdi, Eliana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdham, Khaled, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarker, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhirfan, Luna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhirfan, Luna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMango,